{{distinguish|Nawab Kapur Singh}}
{{Use Indian English|date=December 2015}} {{Infobox officeholder |name = Kapur Singh |image = |office = |president = |term_start = |predecessor = |office1 = [[Deputy Commissioner]] |term_start1 = 1931 |term_end1 = 1962 |predecessor1 = |successor1 = |term_start2 = |term_end2 = |predecessor2 = |successor2 = |primeminister3 = |term_start3 = |term_end3 = |predecessor3 = |successor3 = |office4 = [[Member of Parliament]] |term_start4 = 1962 |term_end4 = 1969 |predecessor4 = |successor4 = |office5 = [[Member of Legislative assembly]] |term_start5 = 1969 |term_end5 = 1972 |predecessor5 = |successor5 = |birth_date = 2 March 1909 |birth_place = [[Jagraon]], [[Punjab Province (British India)|Punjab]] |death_date = {{Death date and age|1986|08|13|1909|03|02|df=y}} |death_place = Jagron, [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], India |party = [[Akali Dal]] |otherparty = |spouse = |residence = [[Jagraon]] |children = |alma_mater = [[Lyallpur Khalsa College]], |religion = [[Sikhism]] |signature = |signature_alt = |website = }} {{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}} '''Sirdar Kapur Singh, ICS''' (2 March 1909 – 13 August 1986) was an eminent [[Sikh]] philosopher, theologian, politician-parliamentarian, and a prolific writer of the twentieth century. As a distinguished linguist he had a mastery over English, [[Gurmukhi]], [[Persian language|Persian]], [[Arabic]] and [[Sanskrit]].
== Birth and education == Kapur Singh was born in a farming family at village Chakk in the district of [[Ludhiana]]. His father's name was Didar Singh. He post-graduated from Government College, Lahore. Later he completed studies in Moral Sciences from Cambridge University.<ref>Encyclopedia of Sikhism, Harbans Singh</ref>
== Career in bureaucracy and dismissal == Returning from UK, Kapur Singh joined the [[Indian Civil Service]] (ICS). After serving at a number of administrative posts under the [[British raj]], he was summarily dismissed from service by Chandu Lal Trivedi, the governor of [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], shortly after [[Partition of India|Indian Independence]], while he was serving as the deputy commissioner of [[Kangra district]].<ref name="sakhi" />
Kapur Singh was incensed at a circular issued by the government that targeted his community. Kapur Singh filed a protest and made the circular public and invited the wrath of Chandu Lal Divedi, the governor of [[Punjab, India|Punjab]]. The charges leveled against him were of corruption and [[insubordination]]. Kapur Singh fought a protracted legal battle but was not restored to the administrative service.<ref name="sakhi">[https://archive.org/download/SachiSakhi-SirdarKapurSingh/SachiSakhi-SirdarKapurSingh.pdf Sachi Sakhi Kapur Singh 14.02.13]</ref>
== Politics == On insistence of [[Akali movement|Akali]] leaders, Kapur Singh joined the Akali politics.{{citation needed|date=June 2013}} In 1962, he was elected to the [[3rd Lok Sabha]] as a candidate of the [[Swatantra Party]] from the Ludhiana constituency.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliamentofindia.nic.in/ls/comb/combalpha.htm |title=Members of Lok Sabha |publisher=Parliament of India |accessdate=11 June 2013}}</ref> In 1969 Kapur Singh was elected to the [[Vidhan Sabha]] in the new [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] state.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books/about/Sikh_achievers.html?id=SLnXAAAAMAAJ&redir_esc=y Sikh Achievers, Ranjit Singh OBE and Kripa Shankar, 14.02.13]</ref> He also remained the National Professor of [[Sikhism]].
==Writings== Kapur Singh was a prolific writer. The books written in English by him include Parasaraprasna a classic treatise on Sikhism, The Sacred Writings of the Sikhs (a UNESCO publication), Me Judice (English Miscellany), Contributions of Guru Nanak, The Hour of Sword, Guru Arjan and Sukhmani. Hashish (poems), Saptsaring (Biographies), Bahu Vistaar (Essays), Pudrik (Essays) and Mansur-al-Hallaj (Monograph of a Sufi saint). His works have also been published by [[Guru Nanak Dev University]], [[Amritsar]] and [[Punjabi University]], Patiala. He is also believed to have scripted the Anandpur Sahib Resolution of the Akali Dal.
